{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658861"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20832"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20832"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.09,0.13,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97039"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13707"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20832"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79655"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11660"},{"type":"tags","id":"11661"},{"type":"tags","id":"11778"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97039"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-week foetus is diagnosed with severe oligohydramnios following prolonged premature rupture of membranes that occurred at 18 weeks gestation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely congenital sequence to develop in this foetus?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Potter sequence","Pierre Robin sequence","DiGeorge sequence","Prune belly sequence","VACTERL association"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely congenital sequence to develop in this foetus is \u003Cstrong\u003EPotter sequence\u003C/strong\u003E. This sequence results from severe, prolonged oligohydramnios, which in this case was caused by premature rupture of membranes at 18 weeks gestation. The characteristic features of Potter sequence include pulmonary hypoplasia (due to inadequate amniotic fluid for lung development), limb contractures, and distinctive facial features (flattened nose, recessed chin, prominent epicanthal folds, and low-set ears).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPierre Robin sequence\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by micrognathia (small jaw), glossoptosis (posteriorly placed tongue), and airway obstruction, often with cleft palate. It is not directly related to oligohydramnios.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiGeorge sequence\u003C/strong\u003E results from a deletion on chromosome 22 and includes thymic hypoplasia, parathyroid hypoplasia, cardiac defects, and facial abnormalities. It is not caused by oligohydramnios.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrune belly sequence\u003C/strong\u003E involves deficient abdominal wall musculature, urinary tract abnormalities, and cryptorchidism. While it can be associated with oligohydramnios, it is primarily a result of urinary tract obstruction or malformation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVACTERL association\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-random association of birth defects including vertebral anomalies, anal atresia, cardiac defects, tracheo-oesophageal fistula, renal anomalies, and limb abnormalities. It is not specifically caused by oligohydramnios.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe severity of Potter sequence depends on the timing, duration, and degree of oligohydramnios. In this case, with rupture of membranes at 18 weeks and severe oligohydramnios by 30 weeks, the foetus has been developing with inadequate amniotic fluid for a significant period, making Potter sequence the most likely outcome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Potter sequence is a series of congenital abnormalities resulting from oligohydramnios, including pulmonary hypoplasia, limb contractures, and distinctive facial features.","Oligohydramnios can be caused by premature rupture of membranes, renal agenesis, or other conditions that reduce amniotic fluid.","The severity of Potter sequence manifestations depends on the timing, duration, and degree of oligohydramnios during foetal development."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 10; page 455."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79655"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20832"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79655"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T06:39:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T06:40:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13707"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97039"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11660","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11660"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Concepts in congenital abnormalities","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":9,"createdAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T18:35:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG